05350nam a22006135i 9781847421296DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847421296  a(DE-B1597)646910  a(OCoLC)1290071875  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0510002bisacsh00aTackling men's violence in families :bNordic issues and dilemmas /ced. by Maria Eriksson, Marianne Hester, Suvi Keskinen, Keith Pringle. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of tables and figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on contributors -- tIntroduction: Nordic issues and dilemmas -- tChildren, abuse and parental contact in Denmark -- tCommitments and contradictions: linking violence, parenthood and professionalism -- t“Talking feels like you wouldn’t love Dad anymore”: children’s emotions, close relations and domestic violence -- tBypassing the relationship between fatherhood and violence in Finnish policy and research -- tMarching on the spot? Dealing with violence against women in Norway -- tChildren’s peace? The possibility of protecting children by means of criminal law and family law -- tA visible or invisible child? Professionals’ approaches to children whose father is violent towards their mother -- t“Take my father away from home”: children growing up in the proximity of violence -- tNeglected issues in Swedish child protection policy and practice: age, ethnicity and gender -- tTackling men’s violence in families: lessons for the UK -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNordic countries are generally regarded as global welfare role models in terms of their image of being gender equal, child-friendly and culturally tolerant. Consequently, the influence of Nordic welfare systems in transnational academic and policy debates has been immense. By focusing on the vital welfare issue of violence by men to female partners and/or their children, this book seeks to reconsider this over-simplistic image. Drawing on new research from Denmark, Finland, Norway and Sweden, the book critically examines how men's violence in families is perceived and responded to in the Nordic context. It pays particular attention to the links between violence to women and violence to children, children's perspectives, professional discourses and responses, and legal and policy approaches. With clear links between research, policy and practice, the book is highly relevant to a wide audience, including academics, researchers and students in the fields of social work, health, criminology, sociology, social policy, gender studies, European studies and law. It is also recommended reading for welfare managers, practitioners, and policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAbused womenxServices forzScandinavia. 0aFamily violencezScandinavia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh1 aEriksson, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEriksson, Maria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aForsberg, Hannele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHautanen, Teija, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHester, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHester, Marianne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJonassen, Wenche, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeskinen, Suvi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeskinen, Suvi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat